Even bolder and misleading about it was anchor Thorsten SchrÃ¶der (see video and quote above) of the ARD Tagesschau, early yesterday morning.
In a functioning democracy, aÂ good public media editor would make sure that the facts are presented clearly and accurately. But a slimey, manipulative editor might take the chance to intentionally mislead the people, and later defend his action by saying: well, you canâ€™t prove it! and that â€œthere is no reason to be talking about a blatantly false report or the likeâ€œ.
German reporting by ARD and ZDF public television and radio on climate change is no less manipulative. Climate change is real and is happening right now. Never mind the all the cold winters weâ€™ve been having, they keep telling us, ignoring the real data.
Germanyâ€™s green publicÂ media have long been on a mission to upbring citizens on responsible energy use, climate,Â and environmentalism. So we suspect here they just couldnâ€™t pass up the opportunity to remind viewers and listeners that nuclear is bad and kills thousands.
Germanyâ€™s now famous Energiewende â€“ energy transition from fossil and nuclear energy to renewables â€“ is coming under increasing fire from the public due to its trillion-euro and still rising price tag, and the media are desperate for a story to convince the public that it is still â€œthe right thing to doâ€. Fukushima was an opportunity to help do just that.
