Over the long-term, the Arctic is a sort of climate barometer, but one that lags the overall northern hemisphere mean temperature trend. What we saw last fall in the ArcticÂ is in part only a consequence of the warm 2000s decade. By the end of the currentÂ decade, chances are good that we will see the Arctic recovering strongly, in response to an overallÂ cooling of the northern hemisphere.
Spring minimum reaches a 10-year high!
Also, this yearâ€™s global spring minimum reached a 10-year high: just under 16 million sq kmÂ (Figure 3), and was thus about 1.5 million sq. km. more than 2 years ago.

Figure 3: Global sea ice bottomed out at just under 16 million sq. km. This is the highest in 10 years and is the same as 1981! See chart: arctic.atmos.uiuc.edu.area.jpg
Right now overall global sea ice anomaly is almost plus one million sq. km., the highest itâ€™s been in 4 years. Thatâ€™s bad news for the albedo theorists. The upper curve of Figure 3 shows that the minimum global sea ice (reached every spring) was at the highest level in 10 years. This flies in the face of the claims that global sea ice is melting rapidly.
