As they added the word â€œprojectionsâ€ we can assume here they mean the end of the 21st century. Note how sloppy (tricky) they are with the communication byÂ blurring the past and the future. If you read carefully, they seem to be saying no trend from 1951 to 2000, yet their projections show 20% increase by 2100, leading a reader tio believe that there is an overall upward trend. If a reader doesnâ€™t read carefully, then he may easily get the idea that there is a â€œ20% trendâ€ The reality however is: their real observations show no trend, but their crystal balls foretell a 20% increase by 2100.
Should we believe the DWD crystal balls? Like Richard Feynman said: â€œIf the observations donâ€™t match your guess, then your guess is wrong. Thatâ€™s all there is to it.â€ It doesnâ€™t matter how many awards you got, how renowned the newspapers say you are, or if you think you won a Nobel Prize, or if your are the director of the Weather Service â€“ itâ€™s wrong.
