One look at the numbers shows: Coalâ€™s share of the USAâ€™s energy mix has been steadily dropping since 2007, from 48.9% to 37.4% in 2012. On the other hand, the share of natural gas has gone from 21.7% to 30.4% for the same time period.â€
Americaâ€™s use of renewable energy has also increased, but are still practically insignificant in the overall energy mix. Obamaâ€™s initiative is one that tries to grab credit for what the free-market economy is doing on its own already. As a result of the reduction in coal, Krahmer writes:
American CO2 emissions in the same time period dropped 13.5%. Of course it would not be serious to make a straight line extrapolation to the year 2030, but one can see that gas in the USA will continue its boom and that it will lead to a shift in the energy mix in favor of gas. Obamaâ€™s climate promises are only anticipating a development that is completely independent of any measures by the US government. In other words: Itâ€™s a reduction in US-CO2 emissions that is based on the fortune of having huge gas reserves at its disposal,Â and it is going to cost the USA nothing. Making promises that donâ€™t cost anything is easy. And Obama did precisely that at his recentÂ speech atÂ Georgetown University.â€
Krahmer then asks what shall the USA do with its vast coal reserves, which the country will no longer need. Krahmer writes that the answer is a no-brainer:
The coal will be exported. In 2012 the USA exportedÂ 125.7 million tonnes. In 2007 the amount was only 59.1 million tonnes. In just five years the USA was able to double its coal exports. The grateful customers of this American coal just happens to be self-anointed climate protection bulwark Europe, which in 2012 took in half of the total US coal exports. When Obama is serious about his climate promises, then he is not casting into question â€“ as he announced â€“Â the financial support for coal power plant construction in foreign countries, but ratherÂ the export of American coal. Because this is not to be expected, nothing more needs to be said in regards to the free trade agreement with Europe.â€
